Linkage disequilibrium

the co-occurrence of allele-pairs within chromosomes in a population at frequencies unexpected given the overall frequencies of each allele in the population assuming random assortment between alleles

  • can't assume random assortment
  • SNP-pairs separated by differing distances will have different thresholds to define "interesting" values of LD
  • The recombination rate of G. f. fuscipes is not well established
  1. distance between loci is inversely proportional to the rate of recombination between syntenic loci.
  2. because of differing recombination rates.

Brief Update

Bayesian LD thresholding

How do we build a Bayesian model?!

  1. What kind of probability distribution would you use if you wanted to GENERATE your data?
  2. What are the parameters that the distribution needs to describe itself?
    • Normal: mean and standard deviation
  3. What kinds of distributions could be used to randomly vary the choice of values to feed into your model's parameters?

What does the data tell us about how our model should look?

  • Data is bounded between 0 and 1
  • Probably not N()
  • Continuous
  • Needs to accommodate two peaks

The Beta distribution mostly fits these qualities:

  • parameters: alpha and beta
  • bounded by 0 and 1 non-inclusive
  • VERY flexible shapes can deal with two peaks
  • just need to deal with the boundary issue

Some of our data have values of 0 or 1.

So I needed to scale our data slightly:


((xi0.5))+0.5

  • shift data to the left by 0.5
    • 0.5 >> 0
    • 1 >> 0.5
    • 0 >> -0.5
  • multiply all points by factor
  • shift the points back to the right by 0.5
  1. What kind of probability distribution would you use if you wanted to GENERATE your data?
    • Beta
  1. What are the parameters that the distribution needs to describe itself?
    • Beta: and
    • both can take any positive value.
  1. What kinds of distributions could be used to randomly vary the choice of values to feed into your model's parameters?
    • We have data so we can inform our prior expectations of the parameter's behavior
  • but we know what our data look like so we dont have to consider ALL values in the Natural set

The model:

  • ovals are probability distributions
  • circles are modeled parameters of a parent distribution
  • grey oval means the distribution considers observed data.

Thresholding results

How many SNP-pairs:

6735 at p-value of <= 0.05
5284 at <= 0.01.

Lowest accepted r2:

0.82

How much better than setting threshold at 0.82?

(rough sensitivity)

80% more *selective*

Not surprisingly, they ALL have r^2 very close to 1, so it does not make sense to compare the filtered pairs to ALL SNP-pairs, but there are 14845 pairs that have r^2 = 1. So I AM being a little discriminatory (selectivity). However, I am also able to pick pairs that have r^2 values as low as 0.82, so my sensitivity is also better than just selecting some naive and HIGH r^2 threshold.

Compared to a hypothetical naive threshold of r^2 >= 0.82, which matches the sensitivity of my method, my method is 80% more selective.
